\b
\p For forty years the land lay safe.

\c 6
\v 1 But the Israelites did what was evil in the sight of the Eternal, and the Eternal handed them over to Midian for seven years.
\v 2 Midian gained the upper hand over Israel; it was to escape Midian that the Israelites made hiding-places among the mountains, caves, and strongholds.
\v 3 Whenever Israel had sown their crops, Midian and Amâlek and the Bedawin would come up raiding,
\v 4 and, entrenching themselves, would destroy the produce of the country as far south as Gaza; they left Israel nothing to live on, neither sheep nor ox nor ass.
\v 5 For they would come up with their cattle, tents and all, swarming like locusts; they and their camels were past numbering, and their coming was the ruin of the country.
\v 6 So Israel was greatly reducing, owing to Midian.
\v 7 The Israelites cried to the Eternal, and, when the Israelites cried to the Eternal on account of Midian, 
\v 8 the Eternal sent the Israelites a prophet, who gave them this message from the Eternal, God of Israel: “I brought you out of Egypt, I brough you from that slave-pen,
\v 9 I rescued you from the power of Egypt and from the grip of all your oppressors, I dispossessed your foes in front of you and gave you their land,
\v 10 and I said to you, I am the Eternal, your God; you must not revere the gods of the Amorites in whose land you are living. But you have not heeded what I said.”
\p
\v 11 Now the angel of the Eternal came and sat down under the sacred tree at Ophrah, which belonged to Joash the Abiezrite. His son Gideon was beating out some what inside the winepress, to save it from Midian;
\v 12 and to him the angel of the Eternal appeared, saying, “You stalwart hero, the Eternal is with you!”
\v 13 “The Eternal with us, my lord?” said Gideon. “Then why has all this happened to us? Where are all his deeds of wonder that our fathers recounted to us? They said, ‘Did not the Eternal bring us out of Egypt?’ But now the Eternal has thrown us aside, he has abandoned us to Midian!”
\v 14 The Eternal turned to him and said, “Go with this strength of your own, and rescue Israel from Midian. Am I not sending you?”
\v 15 “But, my lord,” said Gideon, “how am I to rescue Israel? My sept is the weakest in Manasseh, and I have least weigh tin my family.”
\v 16 The Eternal said to him, “I will be with you, and you shall defeat Midian, every man of them.” 
\v 17 And Gideon said to him, “If I have found favour with you, pray let me have a proof that you are speaking to me;
\v 18 pray do not leave until I come back and offer you my present.” “I will wait till you return,” he answered.
\v 19 So Gideon went indoors, prepared a kid, and made a bushel of flour into unleavened cakes; the meat he put in a basket, the broth in a pot, and then he brough tout the food and presented it to him under the sacred tree.
\v 20 But the angel of God said to him, “Take the meat and the unleavened cakes, and put them on the rock yonder; pour out the broth.” 
\v 21 He did so; and the angel of the Eternal, reaching out the tip of the stick in his hand, touched the meat and the unleavened cakes. Then fire spurted out of the rock and burned up the meat and the unleavened cakes.
\v 22 So Gideon realized it was the angel of the Eternal. “Alas! my lord the Eternal!” he cried, “I have seen the angel of the Eternal face to face!”
\v 23 But the Eternal said to him, “All is well, have no fear; you are not to die!”
\v 24 Then the angel of the Eternal vanished from his sight, and Gideon erected an altar to the Eternal on the spot, calling it “Allswell-Eternal.” It stands to this day at Ophrah which belongs to the Abiezrites.
\v 25 That very night the Eternal said to him, “Take ten of your servants, and take a seven-year-old bull; pull down the altar of Baal that belongs to your father, cutting down the sacred pole beside it,
\v 26 and then erect an altar in due form to the Eternal your God on the summit of this stronghold, burning the bull in sacrifice with the wood of the sacred pole that you are to cut down.”
\v 27 So Gideon took ten of his servants and did as the Eternal told him; but he did it by night; so terrified was he of his father’s family and of the townsfolk, that he dared not do it by day.
\v 28 When the townsfolk rose in the morning, there was Baal’s altar broken down, the sacred pole cut down, and the bull sacrificed on the altar that had been erected!
\v 29 They said to each other, “Who has done this?” And after making strict inquiry they found that Gideon the son of Joash had done it.
\v 30 So the townsfolk said to Joash, “Bring out your son; he must die. He has broken down Baal’s altar and cut down the sacred pole beside it.” 
\v 31 But Joash said to all his opponents, “And are you going to fight Baal’s battles? If he is a god, let him fight for himself!”
\v 32 So Gideon was called that day “Jerubbaal” (or Baalfight), meaning, “Let Baal fight with him, since he broke down his altar!”
\p
\v 33 Then all the Midianites and the Amalekites and the Bedawin mustered, crossed the Jordan, and encamped on the plain of Jezreêl.
\v 34 But the spirit of the Eternal took hold of Gideon; he sounded the alarum, calling the Abiezrites to arms,
\v 35 sent messengers all through Manasseh, calling them to arms, and also through Asher, Zebulun, and Naphtali, who marched out to battle.
\v 36 Then Gideon said to God, “If thou art going to rescue Israel by me, as thou hast said—
\v 37 here I lay a fleece of wool upon the threshing-floor; if dew falls only on the fleece, and all the ground is dry, then I shall be sure that thou art going to rescue Israel by me, as thou hast said.”
\v 38 This did happen. When he rose next morning, he wrung the fleece and squeezed out dew enough to fill a bowl.
\v 39 And Gideon said to God, “Let not thin anger blaze hotly against me; I will ask only one thing more. Pray let me try one more test with the fleece: pray let the fleece alone be dry, with dew on all the ground.”
\v 40 That night, God did it; the fleece alone was dry, and dew lay on all the ground.

\c 7
\v 1 So Jerubbaal (that is, Gideon) and all his men rose early and encamped beside the spring of Harod, the Midianite camp lying north of Gibeath-Ham-môreh on the plain.
\v 2 But the Eternal said to Gideon, “There are too many men with you, for me to hand over the Midianites; Israel might glory over me by claiming, ‘My own hand has won the victory.’
\v 3 Come now, issue this proclamation to the people, that ‘anyone who is terrified and trembling must go home.’ ”  Gideon applied this test, and twenty-two thousand went home, leaving ten thousand.
\v 4 “There are still too many,” said the Eternal to Gideon; “take them down to the water, and let me sift them there; whenever I tell you, ‘this man shall go with you,’ he is to go with you, and whenever I tell you, ‘this man shall not go with you,’ he is not to go.”
\v 5 So Gideon took them down to the water. And the Eternal said, “Place on one side everyone who laps up the water with his tongue like a dog, and place on the other side everyone who kneels down to drink.”
\v 6 The men who lapped numbered three hundred; all the others knelt down to drink the water, putting their hands to their lips.
\v 7 Then the Eternal said to Gideon, “By the three hundred men who lapped I will rescue you and put Midian into your hands; let all the rest go home.”
\v 8 So he sent all the Israelites home, every many of them, keeping only the three hundred, who took the pitchers belonging to the others and their trumpets. Now the camp of the Midianites lay below him in the valley.
\v 9 And that very night the Eternal said to him, “Get away down and attack the camp; I put it in your hands.
\v 10 If you are afraid to make an attack, steal down to the camp with your page Purah,
\v 11 and listen to their talk; that will encourage you to attack the camp.” So down he stole with his page Purah to the outposts of armed sentries round the camp.
\v 12 The Midianites and the Amalekites and all the Bedawin were lying along the valley in swarms, like locusts, and their camels were past counting, as numerous as the sand on the seashore.
\v 13 When Gideon arrived, one man was telling his comrade a dream. “I had a dream,” he was saying; “there was a barley-cake rolling into the camp of Midian! It reached one tent and knocked it right over!”
\v 14 His comrade replied, “That is the men of Israel! God puts Midian and all the camp into their hands!”
\v 15 When Gideon heard the dream told and explained, he knelt down. Getting back up to the camp of Israel, he said, “Up to your feet! The Eternal puts the camp of Midian into your hands!”
\v 16 Then he divided the three hundred men into three companies, furnishing them all with trumpets and empty pitchers and torches inside the pitchers.
\v 17 “Watch me,” he said, “and do as I do; whenever I reach the outskirts of the camp, then you must do as I do;
\v 18 whenever I blow the trumpet, I and all my men, blow you the trumpet also all round the camp, crying, ‘For the Eternal and for Gideon!”
\v 19 So, when Gideon and his hundred men reached the outskirts of the camp at the beginning of the middle watch, just when the guard had been posted, they blew their trumpets and smashed the pitchers in their hands.
\v 20 All three companies blew their trumpets and shattered their pitchers, holding the torches in their left hand and the trumpets in their right, and shouting, ‘A sword for the Eternal and for Gideon!’
\v 21 They stood where they were, all round the camp, and the whole army, wakening up, fled with a wild cry; 
\v 22 when the three hundred blew their trumpets, the Eternal set every man’s sword against his fellow throughout all the army, and they fled as far as Beth-shittah, in the direction of Sererah, as far as the edge of Abel-mehôlah near Tabbath.
\v 23 From Naphtali and Asher and all Manasseh the Israelites were summoned to pursue Midian,
\v 24 and Gideon sent messengers all over the highlands of Ephraim, saying, “Come down against Midian and seize the streams as far as Beth-bârah, seize the Jordan against them.” So all the men of Ephraim mustered, seized the streams as far as Beth-bârah, seized the Jordan also,
\v 25 and captured the two chiefs of Midian, Oreb and Zeêb; Oreb they killed at Oreb’s Rock, Zeêb at Zeêb’s winepress, in their pursuit of Midian, and they brought the heads of Oreb and Zeêb to Gideon on the east side of the Jordan.

\c 8
\v 1 The men of Ephraim then asked him, “What do you mean by treating us like this?—you never summoned us when you started the attack on Midian!” Bitterly did they upbraid him.
\v 2 But he replied, “What have I done, after all, compared to what you have? Surely what Ephraim has gleaned is richer than the full vintage of Abiezer.
\v 3 God has put the chiefs of Midian into your hand, Oreb and Zeêb. What have I been able to achieve, compared with you?” As he said that, their anger at him melted.
\v 4 When Gideon reached the Jordan and crossed it, he and his hundred men, they were worn out and famishing.
\v 5 So he asked the men of Sukkoth, “Pray give my followers some loaves of bread, for they are worn out; we are in pursuit of Zebah and Zalmunna, the Midianite kings.
\v 6 “Give bread to your forces?” said the headmen of Sukkoth. “Are Zebah and Zalmunna already in your hands?”
\v 7 Gideon answered, “Very well, as soon as the Eternal has put Zebah and Zalmunna into my hands, I will trample you naked among thorns of the desert and thistles!”
V 8 He then marched up to Penûel and asked the men of Penûel for the same food; but they answered like the men of Sukkoth.
\v 9 So he told the men of Penûel, “When I come back in triumph, I will demolish this hold of yours!”
\v 10 Zebah and Zalmunna were at Karkor with their troops, about fifteen thousand of them—all that was left of the nomad host; for a hundred and twenty thousand warriors had fallen.
\v 11 Gideon marched up by the caravan route east of Nobah and Jogbehah, and attacked the army, which lay off its guard.
\v 12 Zebah and Zalmunna took to flight, but he pursued them and captured Midian’s two kings, Zebah and Zalmunna, while their whole army was panic-stricken.
\v 13 Then Gideon the son of Joash returned from the battle, from the pass of Heres.
\v 14 He caught a lad who belonged to Sukkoth, who, on being questioned, wrote down for him a list of the headmen of Sukkoth and its sheikhs, seventy-seven of them;
\v 15 and on reaching the men of Sukkoth he said, “Here are Zebah and Zalmunna! You taunted me about them, saying, ‘Give bread to your forces? Are Zebah and Zalmunna already in your hands?’ ”
\v 16 Whereupon he laid the sheikhs of the town upon thorns of the desert and thistles, and trampled down these men of Sukkoth.
\v 17 He also demolished the hold of Penûel and killed the men of the town.
\v 18 Then he asked Zebah and Zalmunna, “Who were the men you killed at Tabor?” “Men like yourself,” they retorted, “each like a monarch!”
\v 19 “They were my own brothers,’ he said, “the sons of my mother. By the Eternal, if you had spared them, I would not be slaying you.”
\v 20 Then he told his eldest son Jether to go and slay them. But the lad did not draw his sword; he was afraid, for he was still a lad.
\v 21 “Come and slay us yourself,” said Zebah and Zalmunna, “a man strikes a man’s blow!” So Gideon went and killed Zebah and Zalmunna; he also took the collars from their camels.
\p
\v 22 The Israelites then said to Gideon, “Rule over us, you and your son and your son’s son, for you have rescued us from Midian.”
\v 23 But Gideon said to them, “I will not rule over you, nor shall my son rule over you; the Eternal shall rule over you.”
\v 24 Gideon said to them, “But let me ask you a favour; let every man of you give me the ear-rings from his booty” (they were gold ear-rings, for the men had been Ishmaelites).
\v 25 “Gladly,” they answered. So they spread out a mantle, and every many threw his ear-rings into it.
\v 26 The weight of the golden ear-rings which he had asked amounted to seventy pounds, in addition to the collars and pendants and the purple robes worn by the kings of Midian and the collars from their camels.
\v 27 Gideon made out of this an ornamental idol, which he set up in his native town of Ophrah; all Israel faithlessly resorted to it, until it proved a danger to Gideon and his household.
\v 28 Thu were the Midianites subdued by Israel; they never raised their heads again. During the lifetime of Gideon the land lay safe.
\p
\v 29 Jerubbaal (or, Gideon) the son of Joash went to reside in his own house at Ophrah;
\v 30 he had seventy sons of his own body, for he had many wives,
\v 31 and his concubine, who lived at Shechem, also bore him a son, whom he called Abimelek.
\v 32 At a good old age Gideon the son of Joash died, and he was buried in the tomb of his father Joash at Ophrah, which belongs to the Abiezrites.
\v 33 [[No sooner had Gideon died than the Israelites again went faithlessly astray after the Baals, and made Baal-berith their god.
\v 34 The Israelites forgot the Eternal, their God who had rescued them from all their foes on every side,
\v 35 and they ill-treated the family of Jerubbaal (or Gideon), after all the good service he had rendered to Israel.]]
